    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-12-02T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-12-02T14:00:00-05:00" n="417"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d417">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857M331/51</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-12-02T14:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 2, 1916, 2 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4116. Your 5807, October 30.<note n="1" xml:id="d417fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    Report of the German Government on the sinking of the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Marina</hi>, which the Department has <pb facs="0600" n="314"
                        xml:id="pg_314"/> received, states steamer was painted gray, displayed no
                    flag, and had a wooden superstructure on deck for the transportation of horses
                    similar to those he had observed in use in the Dardanelles operations, and that
                    the <hi rend="italic">Marina</hi> was actually used as a horse-transport steamer
                    in the service of the British Government.</p>
                <p>Please ascertain officially and definitely as to whether <hi rend="italic"
                        >Marina</hi> was in any way in the service of the British Government at time
                    of sinking, and if so, how long she had been in such service, and if not, when
                    she ceased to be in the British service. Was it customary for her to be in the
                    service of the British Government while transporting horses from the United
                    States to Europe and in private use on the home voyage? Was she coming to the
                    United States to take another ship-load of horses to Europe?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
